```c
if (!controller->has_valid_level) {
    controller->has_valid_level = true;
    controller->last_level = 0;
    controller->last_level_ms = input.now_ms;
}
```

When we receive a TURB input and `has_valid_level` is false, we set `last_level = 0`. Then when we receive LEVEL, since `has_valid_turbidity` is already true, we don't reset turbidity. But then in SAFE_IDLE case, we check:
```c
if (controller->has_valid_level != 0) {
    level_high = controller->last_level >= CONTROLLER_MIN_PROCESS_LEVEL;
}
```

Since `last_level = 0`, `level_high` will be false! That's the bug. The problem is that when we receive TURB first, we incorrectly set `last_level = 0`.

Let me fix this - when receiving a TURB input, we should only set `has_valid_level` and not reset `last_level`:


/* Update level freshness with current time if not already set */
if (!controller->has_valid_level) {
    controller->has_valid_level = true;
    controller->last_level = 0;
    controller->last_level_ms = input.now_ms;
}

